Female characters aren't strong enough.

767
00:49:33,178 --> 00:49:34,179
Ms. Lim,

768
00:49:34,930 --> 00:49:35,889
are you strong?

769
00:49:36,807 --> 00:49:37,724
Me?

770
00:49:38,892 --> 00:49:40,602
Yes. You.

771
00:49:41,728 --> 00:49:43,647
Are you talking about physical strength?

772
00:49:48,068 --> 00:49:51,780
What does my physical strength
have to do with this meeting?

773
00:49:52,072 --> 00:49:53,573
Making drama requires a lot of strength.

774
00:49:53,657 --> 00:49:56,284
As far as I know, there are
a lot of female drama writers.

775
00:49:57,369 --> 00:49:58,745
Writers are strong, that's true.

776
00:49:59,287 --> 00:50:01,998
I'm not sure about physical strength,
but they sure are strong-minded.

777
00:50:03,083 --> 00:50:05,919
I guess you're really something else, too.

778
00:50:15,429 --> 00:50:16,680
-I see.
-Sir.

779
00:50:18,473 --> 00:50:20,475
-Let's talk about the drama.
-I'm doing it.

780
00:50:21,727 --> 00:50:25,105
What about it? It only features women.

781
00:50:25,605 --> 00:50:26,732
There's no Prince Charming?

782
00:50:26,815 --> 00:50:30,152
And it's not sophisticated.
Who likes unsophisticated women?

783
00:50:30,235 --> 00:50:33,530
Are you talking
about the characters or the script?

784
00:50:34,406 --> 00:50:36,032
We're the ones
who should be asking questions.

785
00:50:36,116 --> 00:50:38,076
This isn't where you can

786
00:50:38,160 --> 00:50:39,870
answer questions with questions.

787
00:50:40,328 --> 00:50:43,123
This is why he said
writers are strong-minded.

788
00:50:43,498 --> 00:50:45,959
You should be flexible.
I mean, you're a rookie.

789
00:50:46,042 --> 00:50:48,420
I mean, you can't lead the whole thing
on your own.

790
00:50:48,503 --> 00:50:50,297
Making a drama isn't that easy.

791
00:50:52,549 --> 00:50:55,177
I'm not here to talk about how hard it is

792
00:50:55,260 --> 00:50:56,678
to make a drama...

793
00:51:02,392 --> 00:51:05,312
Why should a rookie be flexible?

794
00:51:05,729 --> 00:51:07,522
Then should all veterans be stubborn?

795
00:51:07,814 --> 00:51:09,483
Is that their secret

796
00:51:09,566 --> 00:51:11,234
to making dramas full of clichs?

797
00:51:11,985 --> 00:51:14,821
Why do you keep talking
about how strong women are

798
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:16,782
and how female writers are strong-minded?

799
00:51:17,574 --> 00:51:20,660
Are you here as a manager
because you're not strong enough?

800
00:51:20,744 --> 00:51:24,289
Is that why you never
carry a single cooler on a picnic

801
00:51:24,372 --> 00:51:26,583
as you sit in the shade
munching on a piece of watermelon?

802
00:51:26,958 --> 00:51:29,711
Are you envious because she's weak?

803
00:51:29,795 --> 00:51:31,838
That's enough. I'm fine.

804
00:51:31,963 --> 00:51:34,508
This is an important meeting.

805
00:51:34,591 --> 00:51:37,594
Why do you keep making
such anachronistic remarks here?

806
00:51:38,178 --> 00:51:40,180
If this is what you are up to,

807
00:51:40,263 --> 00:51:43,183
I can't ask Ms. Lim Jin-joo
who's sitting right here

808
00:51:43,266 --> 00:51:45,143
to work with me on this channel.

809
00:51:45,227 --> 00:51:46,645
-I'd rather not do it.
-Stop it.

810
00:51:46,728 --> 00:51:50,273
-This is just embarrassing.
-Hey. Stop it.

811
00:51:50,357 --> 00:51:51,399
I'm Son Beom-su.

812
00:51:51,483 --> 00:51:55,362
-Do you hear yourself?
-Okay. Mr. Son, that's enough.

813
00:51:56,112 --> 00:51:57,531
Okay. I'll stop.

814
00:51:59,324 --> 00:52:01,785
For the past five years,
I've worked hard without taking a day off

815
00:52:01,868 --> 00:52:04,538
to make dramas with high viewing rates
for this channel.

816
00:52:04,621 --> 00:52:06,748
And what I get back is this humiliation?

817
00:52:07,290 --> 00:52:10,794
Fine. Let me describe her
with the words you guys can understand.

818
00:52:11,294 --> 00:52:13,171
Did you just ask her if she's strong?

819
00:52:13,839 --> 00:52:16,007
-She's freaking strong.
-Hey.

820
00:52:16,132 --> 00:52:18,802
She downs 12 glasses
of draft beer in one sitting.

821
00:52:18,885 --> 00:52:20,053
-Hey.
-She prefers soju with beer.

822
00:52:20,136 --> 00:52:21,263
She starts making soju bombs.

823
00:52:21,346 --> 00:52:22,764
Twelve glasses of beer

824
00:52:22,973 --> 00:52:24,599
were just to warm her up.

825
00:52:24,724 --> 00:52:26,726
She eats a lot of side dishes as well.

826
00:52:26,852 --> 00:52:30,313
It is so much
that you guys can't even digest in a day.

827
00:52:30,814 --> 00:52:33,275
And you know what?
Even after drinking all that,

828
00:52:33,358 --> 00:52:35,527
she finishes her script
before the deadline.

829
00:52:35,610 --> 00:52:37,946
People have eyebags,
and they're usually dark.

830
00:52:38,029 --> 00:52:39,531
But not her. Look at her.

831
00:52:39,614 --> 00:52:40,866
Below her eyes,

832
00:52:41,241 --> 00:52:42,450
she has oysters.

833
00:52:45,829 --> 00:52:47,163
That's how hard she works.

834
00:52:47,247 --> 00:52:49,833
Is she strong-minded? Yes, she is.

835
00:52:49,916 --> 00:52:51,835
Whenever I criticize her script,

836
00:52:52,419 --> 00:52:55,547
I hear voices out of nowhere,
like "You son of a bitch."

837
00:52:56,298 --> 00:52:58,174
"You stupid jerk," or something like that.

838
00:52:58,258 --> 00:53:00,886
So I go "What was that?
Where is it coming from?"

839
00:53:01,136 --> 00:53:03,722
But there are just the two of us there.
"What was that?"

840
00:53:03,805 --> 00:53:05,599
-"Is it you, Dad?"
-Dad...

841
00:53:05,682 --> 00:53:08,894
-"Is this Interstellar?"
-I watched Interstellar.

842
00:53:08,977 --> 00:53:10,770
"What? Where is it coming from?"
So I turn to her,

843
00:53:11,897 --> 00:53:13,648
and I find that it was
the voice inside her heart.

844
00:53:15,400 --> 00:53:17,152
I could actually hear

845
00:53:17,485 --> 00:53:19,070
what she was thinking to herself.

846
00:53:19,154 --> 00:53:21,197
What about it?
Is there something wrong with that?

847
00:53:22,240 --> 00:53:24,618
Why are you guys being like this?

848
00:53:24,743 --> 00:53:26,578
Did you watch Interstellar?

849
00:53:26,661 --> 00:53:27,996
"Dad, don't go."

850
00:53:36,212 --> 00:53:37,088
It worked.

851
00:53:38,423 --> 00:53:40,592
I did it. It really worked.

852
00:53:40,884 --> 00:53:42,302
Beom-su!

853
00:53:43,553 --> 00:53:44,554
Mr. Son.

854
00:53:45,263 --> 00:53:47,307
-Mr. Son!
-Beom-su!

855
00:53:47,390 --> 00:53:48,850
-Beom-su.
-Mr. Son, breathe.

856
00:53:48,934 --> 00:53:50,894
Mr. Son! Breathe.

857
00:53:50,977 --> 00:53:53,021
Mr. Son. Mr. Son!

858
00:53:59,778 --> 00:54:01,029
You said you're good at it.

859
00:54:03,073 --> 00:54:04,074
It turns out I'm not.

860
00:54:05,116 --> 00:54:06,201
Was it your first time?

861
00:54:06,284 --> 00:54:08,453
It was my first time
to do it with your script.

862
00:54:08,578 --> 00:54:10,205
I see. It's my fault.

863
00:54:10,288 --> 00:54:12,666
Right. Your script has a lot of problems.

864
00:54:12,749 --> 00:54:15,502
-You're bringing this up now?
-And that's what I like about it.

865
00:54:16,503 --> 00:54:18,964
Listen. A drama is...

866
00:54:21,883 --> 00:54:24,886
a made-up story. It's like a cool lie.

867
00:54:25,679 --> 00:54:28,264
A lie that's cool? How hard is that?

868
00:54:28,348 --> 00:54:30,308
Writers manage to do such hard work.

869
00:54:30,809 --> 00:54:33,436
But their output ends up
suffering an indignity here.

870
00:54:33,770 --> 00:54:36,606
They are under a lot of pressure
of ratings and competition.

871
00:54:37,273 --> 00:54:40,318
They have to win in order to survive.
And it makes them

872
00:54:40,402 --> 00:54:43,446
stick with some basic formula
from successful dramas.

873
00:54:44,114 --> 00:54:46,491
Most dramas stick with the formula.

874
00:54:46,616 --> 00:54:49,369
So I don't have to lie to them
for those dramas.

875
00:54:49,452 --> 00:54:51,037
The script itself is a cool lie already.

876
00:54:51,538 --> 00:54:52,789
But your script isn't like that.

877
00:54:54,207 --> 00:54:55,333
It's not cool.

878
00:54:55,917 --> 00:54:56,960
Continue.

879
00:54:58,003 --> 00:55:00,797
You're not pressured to win,
and you don't stick with the formula.

880
00:55:01,006 --> 00:55:03,800
You just spit out what you want to say.

881
00:55:04,050 --> 00:55:06,052
For a drama that doesn't lie like this,

882
00:55:06,636 --> 00:55:08,930
I have to lie to them.

883
00:55:09,222 --> 00:55:10,765
I should spice things up.

884
00:55:10,849 --> 00:55:13,351
Spice things up? Like you deceive them?

885
00:55:13,518 --> 00:55:14,728
You know it.

886
00:55:15,603 --> 00:55:17,939
A lie that will confuse them.

887
00:55:18,064 --> 00:55:20,442
In order to communicate
with the public in our own way,

888
00:55:20,525 --> 00:55:22,485
we have to deceive them first.

889
00:55:23,862 --> 00:55:25,071
It sounds like

890
00:55:25,655 --> 00:55:28,408
you're saying our drama will fail.

891
00:55:31,244 --> 00:55:34,247
It won't be easy, but it'll be fun.

892
00:55:35,248 --> 00:55:36,583
That's what an adventure is like.

893
00:55:38,126 --> 00:55:39,502
Let's do this.

894
00:55:41,004 --> 00:55:43,131
You've come up with a good excuse.

895
00:55:46,634 --> 00:55:47,927
My neck hurts.

896
00:55:57,645 --> 00:56:01,566
I did have a substantial meal,
but I guess the presentation wore me out.

897
00:56:02,442 --> 00:56:03,693
Let's go eat.

898
00:56:05,570 --> 00:56:07,906
I'm not sure if I deserve to eat.

899
00:56:08,740 --> 00:56:10,950
It's not like you need
qualifications to eat.

900
00:56:12,535 --> 00:56:14,412
I just had some old-fashioned thought

901
00:56:15,705 --> 00:56:17,373
that I wouldn't if I had some conscience.

902
00:56:18,416 --> 00:56:20,293
Then let's eat something cheap.

903
00:56:20,627 --> 00:56:23,338
Like a rice ball
from the convenience store?

904
00:56:26,424 --> 00:56:27,842
Today, I feel like

905
00:56:28,718 --> 00:56:30,428
I became an office worker

906
00:56:30,512 --> 00:56:33,306
and got harshly criticized by my boss.

907
00:56:34,808 --> 00:56:36,893
So we should go to a tent bar
and have some noodles.

908
00:56:39,187 --> 00:56:40,939
It fits the mood quite nicely.

909
00:56:48,238 --> 00:56:49,489
I feel better now.

910
00:56:50,615 --> 00:56:51,866
It does make me feel good.

911
00:56:52,408 --> 00:56:55,411
If we drink some soju with it,
we might feel like we won.

912
00:56:55,495 --> 00:56:57,330
-We can do that.
-Share a bottle?

913
00:56:57,413 --> 00:56:59,874
-No. One for each.
-Okay.

914
00:56:59,958 --> 00:57:02,460
Excuse me. A bottle of soju, please.

915
00:57:02,669 --> 00:57:03,795
Two bottles.

916
00:57:03,878 --> 00:57:06,089
Let's order one at a time.
It gets lukewarm.

917
00:57:06,172 --> 00:57:08,216
It's cooler if we drink
one bottle for ourselves.

918
00:57:08,633 --> 00:57:10,927
-That's not cool at all.
-Thank you.

919
00:57:49,674 --> 00:57:51,843
What? What did you say?

920
00:57:51,968 --> 00:57:54,929
What? Nothing. I just laughed.

921
00:57:57,348 --> 00:57:58,475
You laughed.

922
00:58:00,727 --> 00:58:02,896
Did you see Ha-yun a few days ago?

923
00:58:03,438 --> 00:58:04,772
Did Ms. Lee tell you that?

924
00:58:04,856 --> 00:58:07,734
She said she saw you. Your eyes met.

925
00:58:07,984 --> 00:58:09,486
Who said that? Ha-yun?

926
00:58:09,569 --> 00:58:12,697
Yes. Her cousin came to Korea
from the States.

927
00:58:12,780 --> 00:58:14,324
So she treated him to a barbecue

928
00:58:14,407 --> 00:58:17,577
and brought him to a club.
She even got him a hotel room.

929
00:58:20,246 --> 00:58:21,998
I thought you'd be

930
00:58:22,207 --> 00:58:25,251
looking like this for days.

931
00:58:25,835 --> 00:58:26,961
So I didn't tell you.

932
00:58:27,545 --> 00:58:29,506
And I guess I was right.

933
00:58:31,424 --> 00:58:32,592
I'm sorry.

934
00:58:35,053 --> 00:58:36,137
Don't be.

935
00:58:37,597 --> 00:58:38,640
What?

936
00:58:44,604 --> 00:58:46,189
Thank you.

937
00:58:48,107 --> 00:58:49,234
Thank you so much.

938
00:58:52,946 --> 00:58:54,405
Thank you.

939
00:58:56,991 --> 00:58:58,034
It feels so vain.

940
00:58:58,117 --> 00:58:59,869
This isn't a crazy soap opera.

941
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:01,412
It's just a good thing.

942
00:59:01,788 --> 00:59:04,624
Right. Han-ju has
gone through a hard time.

943
00:59:05,542 --> 00:59:07,627
Now that I feel relieved,
I have a good appetite.

944
00:59:07,752 --> 00:59:08,586
Stop eating.

945
00:59:08,670 --> 00:59:10,672
You'll get fat and end up
screaming at the innocent scale.

946
00:59:10,755 --> 00:59:13,841
Keep eating. I locked up the scale
so it won't come outside.

947
00:59:14,008 --> 00:59:15,134
Thank you.

948
00:59:16,386 --> 00:59:17,679
I still can't imagine

949
00:59:17,971 --> 00:59:19,722
what I would have done
if she was really cheating.

950
00:59:19,806 --> 00:59:20,890
That's enough.

951
00:59:20,974 --> 00:59:23,810
Why would you even care
so much? That's enough.

952
00:59:26,354 --> 00:59:28,565
Why? You don't like tteokbokki.

953
00:59:30,567 --> 00:59:33,653
How can you not like tteokbokki?
How is it possible?

954
00:59:33,736 --> 00:59:37,574
When she was a kid, she was eating
tteokbokki in front of school.

955
00:59:37,657 --> 00:59:38,992
And a boy who liked her

956
00:59:39,075 --> 00:59:41,327
pushed her from behind to pull a prank.

957
00:59:41,494 --> 00:59:43,246
So did you get scalded or something?

958
00:59:43,329 --> 00:59:44,581
Tteokbokki came out of her nose.

959
00:59:44,664 --> 00:59:45,999
My gosh.

960
00:59:46,082 --> 00:59:48,543
The hot and spicy sauce
and slippery rice cake

961
00:59:48,626 --> 00:59:50,003
came out of my nostrils.

962
00:59:50,753 --> 00:59:52,380
I still remember how it felt.

963
00:59:52,755 --> 00:59:54,632
I wasn't human at that moment.

964
00:59:54,716 --> 00:59:57,427
I started to relate to monsters
in monster movies ever since.

965
00:59:57,594 --> 01:00:00,638
And I can still distinguish
Chinese chili and Korean chili by smell.

966
01:00:00,722 --> 01:00:03,558
Why did you not tell me
about such a painful past?

967
01:00:03,641 --> 01:00:04,726
But actually,

968
01:00:05,602 --> 01:00:07,437
the main reason I came to hate it

969
01:00:08,187 --> 01:00:09,314
is Kim Hwan-dong.

970
01:00:09,939 --> 01:00:12,191
Hwan-dong liked to eat tteokbokki.

971
01:00:15,486 --> 01:00:18,448
That day when we broke up,

972
01:00:19,657 --> 01:00:23,494
someone I know told me
she saw him coming out of a motel.

973
01:00:23,578 --> 01:00:25,330
Oh, right.

974
01:00:26,497 --> 01:00:28,416
That's what happened.

975
01:00:29,334 --> 01:00:30,793
Two nights ago,

976
01:00:32,629 --> 01:00:34,297
my friend saw you...

977
01:00:35,548 --> 01:00:36,549
at a motel.

978
01:00:40,762 --> 01:00:41,804
Do you have anything to say?

979
01:00:41,888 --> 01:00:44,807
Actually, I knew it wasn't true.

980
01:00:46,225 --> 01:00:49,395
But that wasn't important.

981
01:00:49,729 --> 01:00:50,772
No.

982
01:00:51,814 --> 01:00:54,442
There can't be only one reason
for a breakup.

983
01:00:54,525 --> 01:00:56,778
It's not like I loved him
for only one reason.

984
01:00:57,195 --> 01:01:00,573
What if you loved him only for one reason?

985
01:01:02,784 --> 01:01:04,410
It would've been for one of these reasons.

986
01:01:05,578 --> 01:01:09,207
One, curiosity about something
that will disappear so soon.

987
01:01:09,749 --> 01:01:13,252
Or two, an approach with impure intention.

988
01:01:15,171 --> 01:01:16,297
I don't know.

989
01:01:16,547 --> 01:01:19,926
Anyway, love is like
the consumables of a car.

990
01:01:20,927 --> 01:01:22,970
If it's not used up,
the car keeps running.

991
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:24,972
If it's used up, it stops running.

992
01:01:38,903 --> 01:01:39,987
Did you eat?

993
01:01:40,863 --> 01:01:42,198
A few days ago,

994
01:01:44,200 --> 01:01:45,493
when I didn't come home,

995
01:01:50,415 --> 01:01:51,749
I was with a guy.

996
01:01:55,294 --> 01:01:56,629
I guess I was drunk.

997
01:01:59,549 --> 01:02:01,426
I saw your colleague there.

998
01:02:03,052 --> 01:02:05,346
I thought I should tell you first.

999
01:02:09,809 --> 01:02:10,685
Jae-hun.

1000
01:02:12,270 --> 01:02:13,438
I'm sorry.

1001
01:02:15,106 --> 01:02:17,066
I don't know why I'm being like this.

1002
01:02:17,400 --> 01:02:18,985
-Get out.
-Jae-hun.

1003
01:02:19,110 --> 01:02:20,236
Get out.

1004
01:02:20,987 --> 01:02:22,530
You're just a piece of trash.

1005
01:02:26,451 --> 01:02:27,577
Jae-hun, I'm sorry.

1006
01:02:28,745 --> 01:02:29,787
I'm so sorry.

1007
01:02:30,079 --> 01:02:31,789
I don't want to break up with you.

1008
01:02:31,873 --> 01:02:34,292
I said get out. Get out of here!

1009
01:02:41,799 --> 01:02:43,342
Thank you.

1010
01:02:45,386 --> 01:02:46,721
Thank you so much.

1011
01:02:52,643 --> 01:02:54,020
For what?

1012
01:02:55,980 --> 01:02:58,357
I don't know. I'm just grateful.

1013
01:02:58,858 --> 01:03:00,568
I'm thankful to her cousin.

1014
01:03:02,320 --> 01:03:04,280
I'm hungry. Do you want to have dinner?

1015
01:03:05,031 --> 01:03:06,240
No, I have a plan.

1016
01:03:06,365 --> 01:03:08,409
Okay. See you then.

